<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-03-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-03-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="771" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d771">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Clayton</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-03-04"><hi rend="italic">March 4,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 656.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            dispatch No. 1274, of the 21st ultimo, containing a report on the arrest
                            of American citizens employed on railroads in Mexico, for negligence in
                            causing accidents.</p>
                        <p>In view of your comprehensive investigation and report, it is unnecessary
                            for you to pursue the subject further, unless you are hereafter so
                            instructed.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>